21:55.214 --> 21:57.983 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Stay with us.

21:58.017 --> 22:03.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": a
newly discovered
solar system sparks hope for
finding alien

22:03.155 --> 22:08.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
life; and an industrial town
putting its hopes
in President Trump's promise to
revitalize

22:08.661 --> 22:10.396 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
manufacturing.

22:10.429 --> 22:16.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: Nearly five million
Syrians have
fled their homeland for relative
safety in

22:16.135 --> 22:18.170 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
surrounding Middle Eastern
countries.

22:18.204 --> 22:22.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some hope to emigrate to Europe
and elsewhere,
and undergo processing at United
Nations'

22:22.208 --> 22:24.243 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
centers throughout the region.

22:24.276 --> 22:29.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Those hoping to come to the U.S.
have an uncertain
future ahead of them, amid the
Trump administration's

22:29.281 --> 22:30.983 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
orders on immigration.

22:31.016 --> 22:35.187 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
From Jordan, special
correspondent Mike Cerre
reports.

22:35.221 --> 22:43.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE CERRE: The long roads for
refugees hoping
to settle in the U.S. and other
countries

22:43.562 --> 22:50.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
start at processing centers like
this one
in the region run by the U.N.
Refugee Agency,

22:50.803 --> 22:53.505 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
UNHCR.

22:53.539 --> 22:59.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Always a tedious and emotional
process, recent
changes in U.S. immigration
policy added a

22:59.178 --> 23:04.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
new level of anxiety for many
refugees, whose
final security screenings and
departure flights

23:05.017 --> 23:11.857 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
were abruptly canceled, while
UNHCR officials
could sort out the implications
of the executive

23:11.890 --> 23:13.692 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
order.

23:13.726 --> 23:17.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Paul Stromberg is the deputy
director of the
UNHCR refugee resettlement
immigration office

23:17.096 --> 23:18.864 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Jordan.

23:18.897 --> 23:23.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL STROMBERG, UNHCR: The
process doesn't
allow, really, to speed up or
slow down the

23:23.302 --> 23:29.675 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people who are traveling, have
completed this
very thorough screening process
that has lasted,

23:29.708 --> 23:32.344 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for each of them, between one
and two years.

23:32.378 --> 23:37.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For many families, the ones who
were about
to leave at the end of that very
extensive

23:37.750 --> 23:40.619 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
process, had to be rebooked on
flights.

23:40.653 --> 23:47.326 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE CERRE: After six years of
war, the nearly
five million Syrian refugees are
still living

23:47.359 --> 23:52.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
within 200 miles of their homes
in neighboring
countries like here in Jordan,
Lebanon and

23:52.464 --> 23:58.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Turkey, with fewer options of
ever being able
to go back, or going forward, as
more Western

23:58.137 --> 24:01.740 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
governments start closing their
immigration
doors.

24:01.774 --> 24:07.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But as we discovered along the
Turkey-Syria
border, settling in the U.S. has
rarely been

24:07.079 --> 24:11.984 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the refugees' first choice, for
geographic
and cultural reasons.

24:12.017 --> 24:17.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Most Syrian refugees have
preferred staying
close to their homeland and
relatives, rather

24:17.790 --> 24:20.859 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
than immigrating to Europe, let
alone the
U.S.

24:20.893 --> 24:26.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RHANA, Social Worker: And, also,
they have
Syrian coffee here, and also the
trademark,

24:26.899 --> 24:28.834 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
it's Syrian.

24:28.867 --> 24:34.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE CERRE: Rhana, an English
literature professor
back in Syria, is now a social
worker, helping

24:34.173 --> 24:37.476 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
her fellow Syrian refugees get
food and housing.

24:37.509 --> 24:42.548 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She believes many refugees'
cultural ties
to the region are holding them
back from going

24:42.581 --> 24:45.417 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
to Europe as much as the
financial and legal
obstacles.

24:45.451 --> 24:51.156 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
RHANA: It depends on the
mentality of Syrian
people.

24:51.190 --> 25:00.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For example, if they find jobs,
and they could
be able to afford living in
Turkey, I think

25:00.065 --> 25:02.501 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they will rather stay in Turkey.

25:02.534 --> 25:06.238 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They don't need to even exert
effort to learn
the language.

25:06.271 --> 25:09.808 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And they share a lot with the
Turkish people.

25:09.842 --> 25:16.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE CERRE: With no end of the
war in sight,
neighboring host countries
closed their borders

25:16.715 --> 25:18.784 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with Syria last year.

25:18.817 --> 25:24.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The overwhelming strain on their
economies
and delays in foreign aid
pledges have forced

25:24.590 --> 25:29.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
them to reduce social services,
prompting
more Syrian and Iraqi refugees
to choose the

25:29.995 --> 25:33.132 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
immigration route, no matter how
long it takes.

25:33.165 --> 25:38.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL STROMBERG: There are over
650,000 registered
Syrians in Jordan, almost 10
percent of the

25:38.470 --> 25:39.438 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
population.

25:39.471 --> 25:41.774 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, many would like to go to
other countries.

25:41.807 --> 25:45.377 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, first of all, those spaces
have to be
made available.

25:45.411 --> 25:46.612 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They can't apply for them.

25:46.645 --> 25:47.780 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They don't get in line.

25:47.813 --> 25:51.517 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They don't come here and demand
anything.

25:51.550 --> 25:57.689 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But through spaces made
available by resettlement
countries, then we will go out
and check who

25:57.723 --> 25:59.658 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
best suits those conditions.

25:59.691 --> 26:06.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE CERRE: The U.S. has taken
far fewer Syrian
refugees per capita than the
other 30 resettlement

26:06.598 --> 26:12.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
countries, fewer than 18,000,
compared to
Canada's nearly 40,000 and
Germany's more

26:12.938 --> 26:15.140 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
than 600,000.

26:15.174 --> 26:20.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The U.S. also has an additional
vetting process
not required by the others.

26:20.212 --> 26:25.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL STROMBERG: As a refugee,
you are dealing
with several different security
agencies,

26:25.884 --> 26:31.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
different security databases,
biometric registration
at different checks, at
different points of

26:31.723 --> 26:37.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the process, face-to-face
interviews at different
points to verify what you are
telling authorities.

26:37.930 --> 26:43.502 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MIKE CERRE: Refuges stay abreast
of the latest
immigration developments on
local news channels

26:43.535 --> 26:48.607 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and through regular contact with
relatives
and friends already in the U.S.

26:48.640 --> 26:54.413 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This Syrian Kurdish refugee
family from Kobani
sold the last of their family
jewelry to pay

26:54.446 --> 26:59.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the rent for their apartment in
an unfinished
building they are living here
until they know

26:59.585 --> 27:01.487 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
where their future will be.

27:01.520 --> 27:07.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MAN (through translator): God's
willing, if
Kobani is liberated, I will go
back.

27:07.726 --> 27:09.828 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I wish I can reach Kobani and
die there.

27:09.862 --> 27:15.868 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MIKE CERRE: Even if the
immigration ban is
permanently overturned or
substantially changed,

27:15.901 --> 27:22.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's had a chilling effect on
many refugees,
who are now not sure if they
still want to

27:22.040 --> 27:26.612 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
go to the U.S. if and when they
get another
chance.

27:26.645 --> 27:35.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," Mike
Cerre reporting
from Amman, Jordan.

27:35.854 --> 27:44.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now to this
week's edition
of Leading Edge.

27:44.263 --> 27:48.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is new excitement tonight
about the
search for possible life in a
solar system

27:48.567 --> 27:50.502 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
beyond our own.

27:50.536 --> 27:56.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Astronomers have identified
seven Earth-sized
planets orbiting a star just a
mere 230 trillion

27:56.775 --> 27:58.777 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
miles or so from our own planet.

27:58.810 --> 28:00.412 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That sounds like a mind-boggling
distance.

28:00.445 --> 28:02.180 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
It is.

28:02.214 --> 28:05.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But researchers say the idea of
life on one
of these exoplanets, as they're
called, is

28:05.951 --> 28:07.719 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
tantalizing.

28:07.753 --> 28:12.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Astronomers, using ground and
space telescopes
operated by NASA and the
European Southern

28:12.224 --> 28:14.326 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Observatory, made the
announcement.

28:14.359 --> 28:17.362 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our own Miles O'Brien is here to
guide us
through the news.

28:17.396 --> 28:22.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First of all, if something is so
far away
-- this is maybe a basic science
question

28:22.134 --> 28:24.636 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- how do we know what we know
and what we
saw?

28:24.670 --> 28:26.138 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It's a good
question.

28:26.171 --> 28:27.439 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You know, think about it for a
minute.

28:27.472 --> 28:31.143 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If it's trillions of miles away,
how is it
even possible?

28:31.176 --> 28:34.646 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, imagine -- the technique is
called transit
photometry.

28:34.680 --> 28:39.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, imagine you're about a mile
away from
a headlight and a mosquito goes
across the

28:39.451 --> 28:41.219 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
headlight.

28:41.253 --> 28:44.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Believe it not, that headlight
is slightly
dimmed by the fact that that
mosquito goes

28:44.690 --> 28:45.657 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
across.

28:45.691 --> 28:47.526 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Well, this is tantamount to what
they do.

28:47.559 --> 28:53.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The planet goes in front of the
star, it dims
ever so slightly, and with a lot
of complicated

28:53.398 --> 28:57.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and sensitive instrumentation,
you can determine
that, in fact, that's a planet.

28:57.636 --> 28:59.404 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They discovered three of them
this way.

28:59.438 --> 29:04.910 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They said, hmm, this is an
interesting, ultra-cool
brown dwarf to look at.

29:04.943 --> 29:06.678 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Let's put some more hardware on
it.

29:06.712 --> 29:08.480 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They set more instrumentation on
it.

29:08.513 --> 29:12.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, sure enough, there ended up
to be seven
Earth-like planets, just about
the size and

29:12.985 --> 29:17.689 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mass of Earth, orbiting this
Jupiter-sized,
ultra-cool brown dwarf.

29:17.723 --> 29:20.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, you say
ultra-cool,
that doesn't mean it's a cold
sun.

29:20.692 --> 29:23.028 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's just not as big or as hot
as ours, right?

29:23.061 --> 29:26.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It's about like
Jupiter is
to us, OK, cooler and smaller.

29:26.565 --> 29:31.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And when we
talk about this
habitable zone, this Goldilocks,
not too cold,

29:31.403 --> 29:35.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not too hot, how do they know
that there are
planets in this group that exist
within that

29:35.807 --> 29:37.643 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
range?

29:37.676 --> 29:40.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: They can measure
the radiation
off of TRAPPIST-1, this
particular ultra-cool

29:40.912 --> 29:45.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
brown dwarf, and figure out the
zone at which
water would remain liquid.

29:45.917 --> 29:47.486 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And that's the key.

29:47.519 --> 29:50.722 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Everywhere we look on this
planet and we find
liquid water, we find life.

29:50.756 --> 29:52.524 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It doesn't matter where we go.

29:52.557 --> 29:57.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in the hunt for potential
alien life,
the thought of finding places
where there

29:57.729 --> 30:00.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is liquid water is what really
intrigues scientists.

30:00.999 --> 30:07.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, these planets are a lot
closer to TRAPPIST-1
than we are to our son, but,
remember, it's

30:07.906 --> 30:09.908 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
smaller and dimmer.

30:09.941 --> 30:12.377 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And they have these very tight
little orbits.

30:12.411 --> 30:14.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's quite likely there
might be water
on some of them.

30:14.880 --> 30:19.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, even with
just a few
weeks that we have been watching
this particular

30:19.751 --> 30:25.323 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
system, what do we know about
what it would
be like to stand on one of these
perhaps rocky,

30:25.357 --> 30:26.458 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
inhabitable planets?

30:26.491 --> 30:28.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It would be a
very interesting
place.

30:28.527 --> 30:33.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For one thing, we believe they
are tidal-locked,
which means -- it's like our
moon facing us.

30:33.732 --> 30:36.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We only see one side of the moon
as it orbits
around.

30:36.368 --> 30:38.970 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
These planets face their star
all the time.

30:39.004 --> 30:41.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So you have got a sunny side and
you have
got a nighttime side.

30:41.973 --> 30:45.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if you're buying real
estate, I would
go on the sunny side of one of
these planets,

