41:16.307 --> 41:17.275 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What did you see?

41:17.308 --> 41:19.077 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What did you hear?

41:19.110 --> 41:19.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DOUGLAS HOLTZ-EAKIN, Former
Congressional
Budget Office Director: Well, I
think a lot

41:19.944 --> 41:22.213 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the things Jared heard.

41:22.246 --> 41:24.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Number one, this is -- these are
stories of
great distress.

41:24.816 --> 41:25.783 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
That's real.

41:25.817 --> 41:27.452 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's palpable, and unmistakable.

41:27.485 --> 41:32.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is also a longing for a
past that it's
not realistic to expect to
return.

41:32.824 --> 41:35.626 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Erie, Pennsylvania, is close to
my hometown.

41:35.660 --> 41:40.231 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's no longer the
transportation hub it was
when we had the Erie Canal and
water transportation

41:40.264 --> 41:42.834 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as the central part of the U.S.
economy.

41:42.867 --> 41:48.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And coal is not the same in the
presence of
Western coal that competes with
it or natural

41:48.406 --> 41:50.208 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
gas that competes with it.

41:50.241 --> 41:54.512 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, a realistic assessment talks
about, what
can their future be, not what
was their past?

41:54.545 --> 41:56.381 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, that -- so,
Doug, start
with that.

41:56.414 --> 42:00.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Help us think about what a
president can do
and look at some of the things
Donald Trump

42:01.018 --> 42:05.056 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is talking about, at least, tax
reform, for
example, tax cuts.

42:05.089 --> 42:10.795 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DOUGLAS HOLTZ-EAKIN: I think
there is an enormous
amount that the president can do
on tax reform.

42:10.828 --> 42:15.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have a tax code that, broadly
speaking,
favors foreign production over
domestic production.

42:15.900 --> 42:20.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A good reform would neutralize
that and shift
things back to the U.S. when
they're driven

42:20.838 --> 42:21.806 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
offshore by taxes.

42:21.839 --> 42:23.608 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That would a great step.

42:23.641 --> 42:25.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That doesn't mean they will land
in Erie or
that doesn't mean they will land
in coal country,

42:25.309 --> 42:27.111 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but it's something that should
be done.

42:27.145 --> 42:31.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, Jared,
would those kinds
of things have an impact on the
workers we

42:32.016 --> 42:33.785 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
saw?

42:33.818 --> 42:36.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JARED BERNSTEIN: Perhaps at the
margin, but
I think we put way too much
weight on tax

42:36.354 --> 42:38.423 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
reform as economists.

42:38.456 --> 42:43.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have had very different tax
regimes while
globalization has been ongoing,
and you have

42:43.895 --> 42:45.930 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
seen what's happened in these
communities.

42:45.963 --> 42:49.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I don't think we can count on
tweaks in
the tax code -- and Doug and I
could probably

42:49.267 --> 42:53.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
agree on some very good ones,
because the
tax code is pretty messed up --
and hope that

42:53.037 --> 42:56.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this globalization toothpaste
will somehow
go back in the tube, which is
what I hear

42:56.874 --> 42:58.576 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Donald Trump promising.

42:58.609 --> 43:00.478 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I agree with Doug.

43:00.511 --> 43:04.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What needs to happen is that
these communities
have to adapt to globalization,
which doesn't

43:04.148 --> 43:06.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mean you can get back jobs that
aren't coming
back.

43:06.584 --> 43:10.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it does mean that you can
make a play
for advanced manufacturing, for
new industries,

43:11.022 --> 43:12.523 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for new types of energy.

43:12.557 --> 43:14.292 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't hear that coming out of
this administration.

43:14.325 --> 43:18.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What about -- one
thing you
do here is pushing individual
companies to

43:18.162 --> 43:20.531 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
stay, right, to not move jobs
offshore.

43:20.565 --> 43:21.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JARED BERNSTEIN: Yes.

43:21.699 --> 43:23.367 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Well, that's mostly public
relations.

43:23.401 --> 43:25.570 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's not a systematic economic
plan.

43:25.603 --> 43:29.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, frankly, I kind of like
when the president
takes the bully pulpit and says,
we want you

43:29.440 --> 43:30.475 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to keep jobs here.

43:30.508 --> 43:31.776 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's kind of old-school.

43:31.809 --> 43:33.277 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But it resonates with me.

43:33.311 --> 43:34.512 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
But it's not...

43:34.545 --> 43:35.680 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: That could be
old-school liberal,
right?

43:35.713 --> 43:37.682 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JARED BERNSTEIN: Yes, but it's
not an economic
plan.

43:37.715 --> 43:42.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not a systematic strategy
that will help
deliver the goods to the kinds
of communities

43:42.987 --> 43:44.822 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we're talking about.

43:44.856 --> 43:46.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Doug, Doug
Holtz-Eakin, what
do you think about that kind of
move and -- that

43:46.724 --> 43:47.992 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
kind of move?

43:48.025 --> 43:50.728 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then there's also the
deregulation that
he talks about.

43:50.761 --> 43:56.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DOUGLAS HOLTZ-EAKIN: I think the
bully pulpit
is fine, but businesses follow
economic incentives.

43:56.300 --> 44:00.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And once you give them a good
chastising,
the economic incentives are
still the same.

44:00.171 --> 44:03.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And unless you change them, over
the long
haul, the results will be the
same.

44:03.441 --> 44:07.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the bully pulpit is great,
but following
through and actually changing
the incentives

44:07.478 --> 44:10.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they have and the kinds of
things that get
produced in these communities is
the key.

44:10.915 --> 44:15.553 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that taking a good,
hard look
at the regulatory state makes
sense.

44:15.586 --> 44:20.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have seen a dramatic decline
in the startup
of new businesses in the United
States.

44:20.625 --> 44:22.093 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's something that's happened
across sectors.

44:22.126 --> 44:25.296 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not just in manufacturing
or just in
retail.

44:25.329 --> 44:27.131 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so there's something going
on there.

44:27.164 --> 44:31.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we know that, when you start
new businesses,
that's when you get the job
growth, that's

44:31.469 --> 44:33.104 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
when you get the new
opportunities.

44:33.137 --> 44:35.640 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's something that I
think any administration
should look closely at.

44:35.673 --> 44:39.544 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: What is the -- I
think, Jared,
you brought up the word hope,
which you heard

44:39.577 --> 44:41.312 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from these people.

44:41.345 --> 44:45.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We heard the woman in Erie say
people who
voted for him, Donald Trump,
they're hopeful.

44:45.850 --> 44:47.952 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
How important is the
psychological factor?

44:47.985 --> 44:51.522 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JARED BERNSTEIN: Well, I think
it's important,
but I also think it's
omnipresent.

44:51.556 --> 44:53.190 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I have been to places like this.

44:53.224 --> 44:57.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you constantly run into
folks like that
who really have hope for the
future.

44:57.795 --> 45:02.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what it is, is that they
want to participate
in the economy.

45:02.199 --> 45:08.673 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Structural changes,
globalization, these kinds
of -- the loss of the unions,
the kind of

45:08.706 --> 45:12.910 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
labor standards kind of eroding,
they have
really hurt these folks.

45:12.944 --> 45:16.447 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what they would like is a
chance to ply
their trade.

45:16.480 --> 45:20.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Like the guy who says, I'm a
hard worker and
hard work is good, that --
again, that resonated

45:20.851 --> 45:24.155 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with me, but he doesn't have the
employment
opportunity.

45:24.188 --> 45:25.923 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Right.

45:25.957 --> 45:26.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JARED BERNSTEIN: So, what we
really ought
to be talking about is how he's
going to get

45:26.991 --> 45:27.959 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that.

45:27.992 --> 45:29.694 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
One idea is infrastructure.

45:29.727 --> 45:32.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can look at those films, and
you see these
places really need some
infrastructure.

45:32.797 --> 45:37.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, this is something that the
Trump administration
has talked about, but it doesn't
seem to be

45:37.034 --> 45:38.002 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
getting anywhere.

45:38.035 --> 45:39.837 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that's a concern of mine.

45:39.870 --> 45:42.640 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: What's a
particular thing that,
if you could wave your magic
wand, Doug, that

45:42.673 --> 45:44.008 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you would like to see?

45:44.041 --> 45:47.111 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DOUGLAS HOLTZ-EAKIN: Well, look,
the reality
is this.

45:47.144 --> 45:49.647 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
You can only have the
infrastructure if you
have businesses that are going
to use it.

45:49.680 --> 45:51.382 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And so that becomes an issue.

45:51.415 --> 45:54.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The reality is that, in the
manufacturing
sector, it's been automation.

45:54.385 --> 45:57.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It takes 10 percent of the
workers that it
used to, to create the same
things in the

45:57.955 --> 45:59.624 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
U.S. and export them.

45:59.657 --> 46:01.559 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And so there are fewer
opportunities.

46:01.592 --> 46:05.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, you need to be the worker
who can take
advantage of those
opportunities.

46:05.796 --> 46:11.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is unsurprising that people
with a college
degree have an unemployment rate
of 2.5 percent.

46:11.235 --> 46:12.970 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's the magic elixir in this
economy.

46:13.004 --> 46:17.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And these communities have too
many people
who have not had the educational
foundation

46:17.308 --> 46:19.110 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to take advantage of that.

46:19.143 --> 46:22.546 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we're missing the programs
that get people
who want to work hard, but do
not have the

46:22.580 --> 46:23.547 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
skills up to speed.

46:23.581 --> 46:24.548 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

46:24.582 --> 46:25.916 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes, go ahead,
Jared.

46:25.950 --> 46:28.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JARED BERNSTEIN: So, here I have
-- kind of
flip the politics a bit.

46:28.386 --> 46:32.156 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm completely for people being
able to get
all the skills they can.

46:32.189 --> 46:37.528 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if you -- you can get be all
educated
and still not have a job that
will suffice

46:37.561 --> 46:39.397 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for you in your community.

46:39.430 --> 46:43.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so here is where I think
Donald Trump
has said something important and
useful.

46:43.367 --> 46:46.270 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And it's not just about
education or infrastructure.

46:46.303 --> 46:47.805 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's about trade.

46:47.838 --> 46:49.674 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's actually the case.

46:49.707 --> 46:54.311 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He's right that these
communities have been
hurt by our large and persistent
trade deficits.

46:54.345 --> 46:56.681 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so we need to take steps to
reduce those
as well.

46:56.714 --> 47:00.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Again, I don't hear them really
talking about
it, other than some tariffs,
which are bad

47:00.384 --> 47:01.352 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ideas.

47:01.385 --> 47:02.720 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But there are good ways to do
that also.

47:02.753 --> 47:05.189 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: OK, Doug
Holtz-Eakin, a last
word here from you?

47:05.222 --> 47:08.959 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DOUGLAS HOLTZ-EAKIN: I think the
trade piece
is vastly overblown.

47:08.993 --> 47:10.861 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't think that's the source
of their problems.

47:10.895 --> 47:14.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you look at the -- even the
tape on Erie,
their problems began in the
'70s, well before

47:14.999 --> 47:19.503 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we saw NAFTA, well before we saw
the famed
entry of China into the WTO.

47:19.537 --> 47:21.739 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
These are deep, structural
trends in the economy.

47:21.772 --> 47:27.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These are places that had
valuable resources,
coal and transportation access,
that no longer

47:27.078 --> 47:29.413 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have those as their economic
playing card.

47:29.447 --> 47:32.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They need to create a new one,
or the people
who stay there simply aren't
going to have

47:32.583 --> 47:34.385 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
an opportunity.

47:34.418 --> 47:36.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right,
Douglas Holtz-Eakin,
Jared Bernstein, thank you both
very much.

47:36.420 --> 47:37.455 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JARED BERNSTEIN: Thank you.

47:37.488 --> 47:39.390 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DOUGLAS HOLTZ-EAKIN: Thank you.

47:39.423 --> 47:43.728 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And for a look at
the extended-length
videos in this series, Betting
on Trump, go

47:43.761 --> 47:50.735 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to the "NewsHour" Web site.

47:50.768 --> 47:57.374 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's at PBS.org/NewsHour.

47:57.408 --> 48:02.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Trump administration today
announced that
it would soon make a major
change regarding

48:02.246 --> 48:07.885 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the contentious issue of
transgender youth
and which bathrooms they use at
school.

48:07.918 --> 48:09.787 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
William Brangham has that story.

48:09.820 --> 48:13.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The Department
of Justice
and Education are expected to
roll back Obama-era

48:14.024 --> 48:19.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
guidance that advises schools to
let transgender
kids use the bathroom that
corresponds with

48:19.597 --> 48:23.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
their gender identity, not
necessarily the
gender they were born with.

48:23.868 --> 48:27.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But if that guidance goes away,
what does
this mean for schools?

48:27.304 --> 48:30.708 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Evie Blad from Education Week is
back to help
us sort it all out.

48:30.741 --> 48:31.709 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Welcome back.

48:31.742 --> 48:32.843 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
EVIE BLAD, Education Week: Thank
you.

48:32.877 --> 48:34.178 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, let's do
this chronologically.

48:34.211 --> 48:37.081 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Last year, the Obama
administration put out
these guidelines.

48:37.114 --> 48:43.654 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They said, if you, schools, have
transgender
students in your schools, let
them use the

48:43.687 --> 48:46.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
bathrooms that correspond with
their gender
identity.

48:46.624 --> 48:48.759 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What's the rationale for that
argument?

48:48.793 --> 48:52.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVIE BLAD: Well, the Obama
administration
argued that the sex
discrimination protections

48:52.963 --> 48:59.970 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Title IX, the federal law,
applied to gender
identity, rather than merely
biological sex.

49:00.004 --> 49:04.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they had heard from many
districts and
states and some educational
groups that there

49:04.842 --> 49:07.678 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was a lack of clarity at the
state and local
level.

49:07.711 --> 49:13.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so they put out this federal
civil rights
guidance to say, not only do you
have to allow

49:13.450 --> 49:17.555 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
these children access to
facilities that match
their gender identity.

49:17.588 --> 49:19.456 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have to respect that on
forms.

49:19.490 --> 49:26.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You have to provide a safe
learning environment
free from bullying based on this
identity.

49:26.463 --> 49:31.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you cannot disclose their
transgender
status if they don't want it to
be disclosed.

49:31.702 --> 49:35.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Now, a lot of
states welcomed
this guidance and said they were
already doing

49:36.006 --> 49:37.708 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
those sort of practices.

49:37.741 --> 49:39.109 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
A lot of states resisted.

49:39.143 --> 49:41.078 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
About a dozen or so sued.

49:41.111 --> 49:42.947 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What was their argument against
this guidance?

49:42.980 --> 49:44.181 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
EVIE BLAD: Right.

49:44.215 --> 49:47.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, so there is actually two
big multistate
lawsuits.

49:47.451 --> 49:51.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, more than 20 states are
litigating the
issue.

49:51.055 --> 49:53.224 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Their argument are -- several
things.

49:53.257 --> 49:58.362 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some made a student privacy
argument, suggesting
that it violated the privacy of
students who

49:58.395 --> 50:04.668 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
aren't transgender to share
facilities with
students who are.

50:04.702 --> 50:09.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And some made a states' rights
claim this
was federal overreach and an
abuse of the

50:09.473 --> 50:14.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
power of the department, that
they weren't
actually interpreting federal
law, but rather

50:14.078 --> 50:16.146 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
creating new policy through a
back door.

50:16.180 --> 50:21.118 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, if, as we
expect, the
Trump administration to pull
back this guidance,

50:21.151 --> 50:25.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what does that mean tomorrow or
next week
if I'm a transgender kid in a
school somewhere

50:25.155 --> 50:26.123 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the country?

50:26.156 --> 50:28.025 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What does it mean for me?

50:28.058 --> 50:32.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVIE BLAD: Well, about 15 states
have anti-discrimination
laws that cover transgender
students.

50:32.129 --> 50:36.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So students in those states,
their reality
would remain the same.

50:36.500 --> 50:39.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there are districts around
the country
that have made the decision on
their own,

50:39.837 --> 50:47.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
long before this guidance, to
put rules in
place that largely mirror what
it requires.

50:47.044 --> 50:51.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But for states and districts
that don't have
those kinds of rules, they're
kind of on their

50:51.782 --> 50:57.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
own to interpret the federal law
and to make
their own determination on what
they think

50:57.821 --> 50:59.757 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
they should do for these
children.

50:59.790 --> 51:03.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Of course,
this is all happening
in the backdrop of a very big
Supreme Court

51:04.028 --> 51:09.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
case that is happening where a
boy in Virginia,
a transgender boy, sued his
school district

51:09.166 --> 51:13.103 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to say, let me use the boys'
bathroom.

51:13.137 --> 51:18.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Does the withdrawal of these
guidelines do
anything to his standing in the
Supreme Court?

51:18.409 --> 51:23.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EVIE BLAD: Well, to this point,
many transgender
students who have won in federal
courts have

51:23.881 --> 51:29.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
won under the argument that the
courts should
defer to federal interpretation
of Title IX.

51:29.687 --> 51:32.389 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so that does take one
argument away.

51:32.423 --> 51:37.561 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Gavin Grimm, the student
from Virginia,
can still go forward, his
attorneys say, arguing

51:37.594 --> 51:42.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about the fundamental meaning of
Title IX,
what was implied when it was
written, and

51:42.733 --> 51:44.735 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
should that apply to him today?

51:44.768 --> 51:49.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: One of the
arguments that
undergirds a lot of this, I
know, is the fear

51:49.340 --> 51:54.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that some people have expressed
that, if you
allow a transgender student to
use the bathroom

51:54.812 --> 52:01.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
according to their gender
identity, that you
might have men masquerading as
women, in effect,

52:01.552 --> 52:04.989 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to get into a bathroom and
somehow get up
to no good.

52:05.022 --> 52:08.359 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is there any evidence that
that's really something
that's going on?

52:08.392 --> 52:10.828 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
EVIE BLAD: I don't believe so.

52:10.861 --> 52:14.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In the districts that have had
these rules
for a long time, they say that
they have had

52:14.465 --> 52:16.567 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
very little problems with them.

52:16.600 --> 52:20.504 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They say that students' requests
to use them
are pretty rare.

52:20.537 --> 52:26.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The most recent estimate on
transgender students
said that transgender children
between the

52:26.543 --> 52:30.581 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ages of 13 and 17, they make up
about 0.7
percent of the population.

52:30.614 --> 52:34.651 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So we're talking about a very
small number
of students here.

52:34.685 --> 52:38.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there is some argument on
the other side
that it can be difficult to
implement and

52:38.722 --> 52:43.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
interpret these rules for such a
confusing
thing as gender identity,
especially when

52:43.093 --> 52:45.062 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it can be in flux for some
children.

52:45.095 --> 52:49.199 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
